The paper deals with natural language inference, which is a core problem in computational linguistics and natural language processing. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also uses deep learning techniques, specifically stacked bidirectional LSTM-RNNs, which are commonly used in machine learning and artificial intelligence, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also mentions achieving state-of-the-art results on the SNLI dataset, which is a benchmark dataset for natural language understanding, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions achieving strong results on multi-domain natural language inference, which could potentially fall under cs.CV (Computer Vision) if the domains involve visual information.
